BLUETONGUE - EUROPE (20): BTV-8, VACCINATION
********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

In this update:
[1] Vaccination, EU countries
[2] Vaccination, The Netherlands

******
[1] Vaccination, EU countries
Date: Thu 3 Apr 2008
Source: Farmers Guardian [edited]
<http://www.farmersguardian.com/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=17463>


Vaccination gets under way as Europe takes its 1st deliveries
-------------------------------------------------------------
Vaccination against bluetongue is under way on the continent as farmers
attempt to get to grips with the disease that has devastated livestock
across Europe. France became the 1st country to roll out the vaccine this
week as Merial Animal Health delivered an initial order of 200 000 doses.
Under an emergency licence, the company has been allowed to distribute the
vaccine to vets in France, who have been urgently vaccinating sheep prior
to export.

The move came after Italy put pressure on France to begin an early
vaccination programme, refusing to accept stock that had not been
vaccinated. Vaccines were ordered by the French Government on 4 Mar 2008
and have been made available in just 6 weeks, despite setbacks at Merial's
Pirbright laboratory.

A spokesman for Merial said: "We did have initial supply problems because
we had been closed down following a leaky valve. Although that was fixed
within 24 hours, we didn't win back our SAPO [Specified Animal Pathogens
Order] licence from DEFRA [UK Department for Environment, Food, and Rural
Affairs] for 3 months, but stock of the vaccine was being produced at our
plant in Lyon and has been waiting to go out."

France has ordered a total of 30 million doses of vaccine, splitting the
tender between Merial and rival firm Intervet, which is also producing
vaccine for the British market. Vaccine stocks have now been ordered
throughout Europe and it is hoped that a successful vaccination programme
could see the disease wiped out in the future.

This week Germany became the latest country to place an order, issuing a
tender for 21 million doses of the vaccine. Stocks have also been ordered
in Belgium and Holland where the disease has also decimated livestock since
it first hit in 2006. Europe is seen as key to the UK's disease status with
the threat of infected midges being blown over the Channel from the
continent. The build up of vaccine stocks across Europe is likely to put
further pressure on politicians in Scotland and Northern Ireland to order
their own stocks.

This week the National Beef Association (NBA) urged the Department of
Agriculture in Northern Ireland to place an order and be prepared if the
disease hits. Arthur McKevitt, NBA's Northern Ireland secretary said: "In
these circumstances it would be sensible for Northern Ireland to carefully
examine whether it should adopt a safety first approach and have vaccine on
hand in case it proves necessary to use it -- or take a risk on import
controls of live animals offering sufficient protection over 2008."

[byline: Jack Davies]

