******
[2] Vaccination, The Netherlands
Date: Thu 3 Apr 2008
Source: Ministry of Agriculture, The Netherlands, press release [in Dutch,
trans. Mod.AS, edited]
<http://www.minlnv.nl/portal/page?_pageid=116,1640333&_dad=portal&_schema=PORTAL&p_news_item_id=23190>


Bluetongue vaccination
----------------------
The minister of agriculture, Gerda Verburg, advises veterinarians to start
the voluntary vaccination against bluetongue in May [2008]. The 1st 2
million doses will be distributed to veterinary practices evenly throughout
the country, according to the number of ruminants (cattle, sheep, and
goats) served per practice. The advice is mainly directed to support animal
welfare and to minimise economical losses.

Veterinarians are strongly advised to make use of the 2 million doses,
available for the spring vaccination, in the following prioritised target
groups: cows (within 2 months before or after their insemination), breeding
rams, lambs intended for breeding, and breeding ewes and goats. There is no
ranking between the groups.

Explaining the said prioritisation, Verburg indicates that the main
bluetongue losses in cattle, last year [2007], were related to reduced
fertility and abortions. The fertility of breeding rams was affected,
likely due to bluetongue. Mortality was significantly high among sheep of
younger age. The inclusion of breeding ewes and goats is based upon export
considerations.

The 4 million doses, which will become available in July [2008], will be
delivered to veterinary practices upon receipt of orders. A specific
mechanism will be applied to safeguard the evenness of vaccine quantities
distributed to the ordering practices.

Bluetongue is present in the Netherlands since 2006; last year [2007], it
caused mainly a high mortality in sheep.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The EU map showing the location of the restriction zones has been
prepared, as updated on 2 Apr 2008, and is available at
<http://ec.europa.eu/food/animal/diseases/controlmeasures/bluetongue_restrictedzones.jpg>.
The entire territories of Germany, the Netherlands, Belgium, Luxembourg,
and Switzerland are coloured red in the map, representing BT restriction
zones. BT restriction zones are composed of protection zones (100 km/62
miles) and surveillance zones (depth of at least 50 km (31 miles) extending
beyond the limits of the protection zone) around the infected farms.
According to EU laws, BTV vaccination can be carried out in protection
zones only. It seems that the entire Belgian and Dutch national territories
are termed protection zones, thus authorised to cover their entire
territories by the due vaccination. In France (south and north west), and
probably Germany and Switzerland (confirmation/information requested),
there are still areas where vaccination is not allowed. Similarly, no
vaccination is allowed in large parts of the UK such as Wales, Scotland,
and Cornwall. The EU rule, prohibiting the vaccination outside the
protection zones, seems to be in need of a thorough study.

The likelihood of successfully controlling and even eradicating BTV-8 in
the affected countries by mass vaccinations of all susceptible domestic
ruminants is debatable. In any event, a comprehensive, total vaccination
does not seem feasible at present in any of the affected countries, due to
shortage of available vaccine and to technical/financial reasons.

Is surveillance in (unvaccinated) sentinel animals, to assess the possible
continued activity and spread of BTV-8, considered in all vaccinating
countries? In traditionally BTV-infected regions outside Europe, where only
sheep are vaccinated, the role of sentinels is played by bovines. However,
European bovines (probably, including immune animals which have undergone
infection previously...) are to be vaccinated.

The Dutch programme with its stepwise timetable and prioritised target
groups makes sense and sounds practical. It will be interesting to obtain
information on the comparable schedules in the other affected countries. -
Mod.AS]
